**Category:** essay-draft practical-knowledge speculative-knowledge Aristotle Aquinas Nussbaum theology

**Abstract:**
Essay dated September 21, 1993, titled "Practical Science." The document examines the distinction between speculative and practical sciences, arguing that knowledge only functions as knowledge when it informs action and is transcended applicationally. It critiques the Aristotelian-Thomistic view that knowledge consists in judgments to be assented to, proposing instead that knowledge has purely instrumental value. The essay applies this analysis to theology, arguing that Aquinas's theology of assent treats faith as "homonymous" (equivocal) with genuine faith because it does not function as faith should. Includes substantial engagement with Nussbaum on Aristotle's De Anima.

**AI Recommendation:** Major theoretical essay on practical vs. speculative knowledge; develops key critique of Thomistic theology of assent.

